It's worth noting the fascinating, if slightly inconvenient, phenomenon of sites that defy simple categorization by county, choosing instead to spread their historical significance across multiple administrative boundaries. These 26 "duplicates" aren't errors, but rather a testament to the fact that history, much like nature, rarely respects arbitrary lines on a map. For instance, the [E. M. Backus Lodge](/E._M._Backus_Lodge) is so captivating it demands recognition in both [Jackson](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Jackson_County,_North_Carolina) and [Transylvania](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Transylvania_County,_North_Carolina) counties. Similarly, the [Beatty-Corbett House](/Beatty-Corbett_House) straddles [Pender](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Pender_County,_North_Carolina) and [Sampson](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Sampson_County,_North_Carolina), while [Bellamy's Mill](/Bellamy%27s_Mill) links [Halifax](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Halifax_County,_North_Carolina) and [Nash](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Nash_County,_North_Carolina).

Then there are the truly expansive listings, such as the [Cape Fear Civil War Shipwreck Discontiguous District](/Cape_Fear_Civil_War_Shipwreck_Discontiguous_District), which, as its name subtly hints, is not confined to a single spot but stretches across [Brunswick](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Brunswick_County,_North_Carolina), [New Hanover](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_New_Hanover_County,_North_Carolina), and [Pender](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Pender_County,_North_Carolina) counties, preserving the watery graves of history. The [Cheoah Hydroelectric Development](/Cheoah_Hydroelectric_Development) similarly bridges [Graham](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Graham_County,_North_Carolina) and [Swain](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Swain_County,_North_Carolina), a testament to early 20th-century engineering. The [Green Park Historic District](/Green_Park_Historic_District) offers its charm to both [Caldwell](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Caldwell_County,_North_Carolina) and [Watauga](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Watauga_County,_North_Carolina), while the [Linville Falls Tavern](/Linville_Falls_Tavern) enjoys the distinction of being recognized in [Avery](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Avery_County,_North_Carolina), [Burke](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Burke_County,_North_Carolina), and [McDowell](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_McDowell_County,_North_Carolina).

Agricultural history finds its dual home in [Long Valley Farm](/Long_Valley_Farm), spanning [Cumberland](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Cumberland_County,_North_Carolina) and [Harnett](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Harnett_County,_North_Carolina), and urban development is reflected in the [Rocky Mount Central City Historic District](/Rocky_Mount_Central_City_Historic_District) in [Edgecombe](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Edgecombe_County,_North_Carolina) and [Nash](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Nash_County,_North_Carolina). The [Upper Town Creek Rural Historic District](/Upper_Town_Creek_Rural_Historic_District) further connects [Edgecombe](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Edgecombe_County,_North_Carolina) and [Wilson](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Wilson_County,_North_Carolina), while the Mount Carmel Presbyterian Church and Cemetery (a site yet to achieve its own dedicated article or illustration, a minor tragedy, I suppose) is recognized in both [Montgomery](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Montgomery_County,_North_Carolina) and [Richmond](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Richmond_County,_North_Carolina). The [Dillard B. and Georgia Sewell House](/Dillard_B._and_Georgia_Sewell_House) graces [Henderson](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Henderson_County,_North_Carolina) and [Transylvania](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Transylvania_County,_North_Carolina), and the [Wyse Fork Battlefield](/Wyse_Fork_Battlefield) extends its solemn presence across [Jones](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Jones_County,_North_Carolina) and [Lenoir](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places_listings_in_Lenoir_County,_North_Carolina).

And then, of course, there's the [Blue Ridge Parkway](/Blue_Ridge_Parkway), a monumental linear park that, with characteristic disregard for human-made divisions, meanders through a staggering 12 counties. It’s a road, a destination, and a historical marvel all at once, proving that some things are simply too grand to be contained. These multi-county listings complicate the neat numerical summaries, but they underscore the complex interconnectedness of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina)'s diverse historical landscape.

